DIV1.P:
TO WHICH IS PREFIXED,
An ACCOUNT of the LIFE and WRITINGS of the AUTHOR;
By DUGALD STEWART, F. R. S. E.

The rarity of double rhymes in English Heroic Verse makes them appear odd, and aukward, and even ludicrous, when they occur. By the best writers, therefore, they are reserved for light and ludi∣crous occasions; when, in order to humour their subject, they stoop to a more familiar style than usual. When Mr. Pope says;
Worth makes the man, and want of it the fellow;
The rest is all but leather or prunello;
he means, in compliance with his subject, to condescend a good deal below the stateliness of his diction in the Essay on Man. Double rhymes abound more in Dryden than in Pope, and in Hu∣dibras more than in Dryden.

In Italian frequently, and in English sometimes, an accent is with great grace thrown upon the first syllable: in which case it seldom happens that any other syllable is accented before the fourth;
Cánto l'armé pietóse e'l capitáno.
Fírst in these fiélds I trý the sylvan stráins.

DIV2.P:
The objects of Touch are solidity, and those modifications of
solidity which we consider as essential to it, and inseparable from it;
solid extension, figure, divisibility, and mobility.
